    &quot;type&quot;: &quot;text&quot;,
    &quot;text&quot;: &quot;Excellent! Now I have a comprehensive understanding of the ChromDetect project. Let me compile the complete report.\n\n## ChromDetect Project - Comprehensive Exploration Report\n\nI&#x27;ve thoroughly explored the ChromDetect project. Here&#x27;s a complete analysis of all six key aspects you requested:\n\n---\n\n## 1. PROJECT PURPOSE\n\n**ChromDetect** is a Python bioinformatics tool designed to detect chromosome-level scaffolds in genome assemblies despite inconsistent naming conventions. It addresses a real problem in genomics: different genome assembly pipelines use wildly different naming schemes for chromosomes (e.g., `chr1`, `Super_scaffold_1`, `SUPER_1`, `LG_1`, `HiC_scaffold_1`, NCBI accessions, etc.).\n\nThe tool helps researchers automatically:\n- Identify chromosome-level vs. unlocalized vs. unplaced scaffolds\n- Classify scaffolds using multiple detection strategies\n- Validate assemblies against known karyotypes\n- Export results in multiple formats for downstream analysis\n- Support cross-species genome comparisons\n\n---\n\n## 2. OVERALL ARCHITECTURE AND STRUCTURE\n\nThe project follows a clean, modular architecture with clear separation of concerns:\n\n```\n/Users/scotthandley/Code/chromdetect/\n├── chromdetect/           # Main package (807 lines of Python)\n│   ├── __init__.py        # Public API exports\n│   ├── core.py            # Core classification logic (463 lines)\n│   ├── patterns.py        # Regex pattern definitions (99 lines)\n│   └── cli.py             # Command-line interface (215 lines)\n├── tests/                 # Test suite (560 lines total)\n│   ├── test_core.py       # Core functionality tests\n│   ├── test_patterns.py   # Pattern detection tests\n│   └── test_cli.py        # CLI integration tests\n├── examples/              # Three example scripts\n│   ├── basic_usage.py\n│   ├── batch_processing.py\n│   └── karyotype_detection.py\n├── .github/workflows/     # CI/CD automation\n│   ├── test.yml           # Automated testing\n│   └── publish.yml        # PyPI publication\n└── Configuration files (pyproject.toml, README, etc.)\n```\n\n**Architecture Flow:**\n1. **Input**: FASTA file (plain or gzipped)\n2. **Parsing** (parse_fasta) → List of (name, length, sequence_sample)\n3. **Classification** (classify_scaffolds) → Uses parallel detection methods:\n   - Name-based detection (15+ patterns)\n   - Size-based detection (relative to N50, largest scaffold)\n   - Karyotype-informed adjustment\n4. **Output**: ScaffoldInfo objects + AssemblyStats + Multiple formats (JSON, TSV, Summary)\n\n---\n\n## 3. KEY FILES AND THEIR ROLES\n\n### Core Source Files\n\n**`/Users/scotthandley/Code/chromdetect/chromdetect/core.py` (463 lines)**\n- **ScaffoldInfo dataclass**: Stores individual scaffold results (name, length, classification, confidence, detection_method, chromosome_id)\n- **AssemblyStats dataclass**: Aggregate statistics (total_scaffolds, n50, n90, chromosome_count, gc_content, etc.)\n- **parse_fasta()**: Efficiently parses FASTA/FASTA.gz files, sampling first 10kb for GC calculation\n- **detect_by_name()**: Pattern-matching based detection with priority rules for unlocalized/fragment patterns\n- **detect_by_size()**: Size-based heuristics (large scaffolds, N50-relative, small scaffolds)\n- **classify_scaffolds()**: Main entry point combining both strategies with intelligent merging\n- **_adjust_for_karyotype()**: Refines classifications based on expected chromosome count\n- Statistical helpers: calculate_n50(), calculate_n90(), calculate_gc()\n\n**`/Users/scotthandley/Code/chromdetect/chromdetect/patterns.py` (99 lines)**\n- **CHROMOSOME_PATTERNS**: 13 compiled regex patterns for chromosome naming conventions:\n  - Explicit (chr1, chromosome_X, etc.)\n  - VGP-style (Super_scaffold_1, Superscaffold_1, SUPER_1)\n  - Linkage groups (LG1, LG_X)\n  - NCBI accessions (NC_*, CM*)\n  - HiC/RaGOO scaffolders\n  - Plant-specific (Pt#, Gm#)\n  - Numeric simple patterns\n- **UNLOCALIZED_PATTERNS**: 7 patterns for non-placed chromosomal scaffolds\n- **FRAGMENT_PATTERNS**: 9 patterns for contigs/fragments\n- **compile_patterns()**: Pre-compiles all patterns for performance\n\n**`/Users/scotthandley/Code/chromdetect/chromdetect/cli.py` (215 lines)**\n- **main()**: CLI entry point with argparse configuration\n- **format_output()**: Renders results in three formats:\n  - JSON: Complete scaffold data + summary statistics\n  - TSV: Tab-separated table for spreadsheet tools\n  - Summary: Human-readable formatted report\n- Supports options: --format, --output, --karyotype, --min-size, --chromosomes-only, --quiet\n\n**`/Users/scotthandley/Code/chromdetect/chromdetect/__init__.py`**\n- Public API exports: ScaffoldInfo, AssemblyStats, classify_scaffolds, parse_fasta, detect_by_name, detect_by_size, pattern constants\n\n### Test Files\n\n**`/Users/scotthandley/Code/chromdetect/tests/test_core.py`**\n- TestN50Calculations: 4 tests for N50/N90 calculation edge cases\n- TestGCCalculation: 5 tests for GC content calculation\n- TestSizeDetection: 3 tests for size-based detection logic\n- TestFastaParsing: 4 tests for FASTA parsing (simple, multiline, empty, missing)\n- TestClassifyScaffolds: 5 tests for full classification pipeline + karyotype adjustment\n- TestScaffoldInfo/AssemblyStats: 2 tests for dataclass serialization\n\n**`/Users/scotthandley/Code/chromdetect/tests/test_patterns.py`**\n- TestChromosomePatterns: Parametrized tests covering 15+ naming patterns (chr, super scaffold, linkage groups, NCBI, HiC, etc.)\n- TestUnlocalizedDetection: 4 parametrized tests for random/unlocalized patterns\n- TestFragmentDetection: 6 parametrized tests for contig/fragment patterns\n- TestNCBIPatterns: RefSeq and GenBank accession detection\n- TestPatternCompilation: Pattern compilation and consistency checks\n\n**`/Users/scotthandley/Code/chromdetect/tests/test_cli.py`**\n- TestFormatOutput: Tests JSON, TSV, and summary output formatting\n- TestCLIIntegration: Integra